@Andreas I don't know.  I can't say I agree with your overall assessment, but I genuinely appreciate you laying it out honestly and respectfully.  

Where I think the distinction lies for me is that this company and more broadly just people in general who are addressing this phenomenon,  are saying we should amend masculinity which is toxic.  These responses appear to be coming from people who are responding to a statement more akin to we should amend masculinity, which is toxic.  That comma is a small, but largely important piece of punctuation.  It's the difference between saying that maleness in its own right is bad and saying that dudes acting poorly devalue maleness.  

As for women being toxic as well in their own ways, sure, that case can absolutely be made and made competently.  But Gillette has not positioned itself as a brand this way and thus that critique wouldn't make much sense when taken in the context of their slogan "the best a man can get".  They are clearly going for a "the best a man can be" angle here, which for better or worse does not necessitate tackling all social ills in one fell swoop.

